    "image": "/blog-images/business-intelligence/Business-Intelliegence-Enhancement-1024x576.png",
    "content": "<h2 id=\"h-the-importance-of-external-data-as-a-driver-of-enhanced-insights-and-efficiency\">The Importance of External Data as a driver of enhanced insights and efficiency</h2>\n<img src=\"/blog-images/business-intelligence/Business-Intelliegence-Enhancement-1024x576.png\" alt=\"\" />\n<p>Context is everything. While your organization likely has a trove of internal data—ranging from customer behavior to supply chain metrics—it’s equally crucial to consider the external factors that influence your business outcomes. Including external data as part of your business intelligence practice helps you understand what’s driving your performance.</p>\n<p>External data can include economic indicators like unemployment rates and median household income, as well as environmental factors such as weather patterns. These elements have a tangible impact on how your business operates and performs. Without a comprehensive understanding of these external influences, you risk making decisions based on an incomplete picture.</p>\n<h2 id=\"h-the-importance-of-external-data-as-a-driver-of-enhanced-insights-and-efficiency\">The Importance of External Data as a driver of enhanced insights and efficiency</h2>"
